<subSubSection pageId="22" pageNumber="123" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1437,151,645]" pageId="22" pageNumber="123">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,511,536]" pageId="22" pageNumber="123">Remarks.</emphasis>
The elongate, down-curving, cylindrical paramere shape is unique in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mickel" authorityYear="1936" box="[1221,1359,511,536]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Lomachaeta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="123" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1221,1359,511,536]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="123">Lomachaeta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. This morphology is superficially similar to that of 
<taxonomicName box="[666,829,549,572]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Lomachaeta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="123" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vacamuerta">
<emphasis box="[666,829,549,572]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="123">L. vacamuerta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, except that species has shorter, straighter parameres. The length and curve, however, are similar to that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pitts &amp; Manley" authorityYear="2004" box="[754,914,583,608]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Smicromutilla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="123" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="beadugrimi">
<emphasis box="[754,914,583,608]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="123">L. beadugrimi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Williams &amp; Pitts" authorityYear="2009" box="[970,1132,583,608]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Lomachaeta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="123" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="snellingella">
<emphasis box="[970,1132,583,608]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="123">L. snellingella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, except those species have dorsoventrally flattened parameres without an apical setal tuft.
</paragraph>
